#compdef atuin-run
# =============================================================================
# atuin-run — Atuin Inc.'s "runbook runner" — a Rust CLI for
#             executing .atrb (Atuin Runbook) files non-
#             interactively or interactively.  Companion to the
#             Atuin shell-history sync platform; atuin-run
#             handles the "runbooks that run" aspect — declarative
#             multi-step playbooks that combine shell commands +
#             environment + variables + control-flow.
#             Distinguishing from Ansible, makefile, Just,
#             Taskfile, and other task runners by:
#               - DECLARATIVE .atrb FORMAT — runbook files combine
#                 shell snippets + step descriptions + environment
#                 variables + per-step interactive prompts into a
#                 structured YAML-like schema
#               - INTERACTIVE TUI execution mode via crossterm +
#                 vt100 — displays runbook progress + per-step
#                 output in a terminal interface
#               - AUTO-DETECTED INTERACTIVE/NON-INTERACTIVE — by
#                 default detects whether stdout is a TTY +
#                 whether CI / NO_TTY env vars are set + reverts
#                 to non-interactive (machine-readable) output
#                 when piped or in CI
#               - ATUIN HUB INTEGRATION — runbook identifier can
#                 be either a local file path (.atrb) OR a remote
#                 @user/name identifier resolved against the
#                 Atuin Hub registry
#               - VT100 EMULATION via vt100 crate — embeds a
#                 full terminal emulator for nested command
#                 output (shows live command output streamed
#                 into a sub-region of the TUI)
#               - textwrap TEXT WRAPPING — every step
#                 description + error message + help text
#                 wrapped to terminal width via textwrap's
#                 first-paragraph + subsequent-paragraph
#                 wrapping algorithm
#             Used by: DevOps teams sharing reproducible
#             multi-step procedures, on-call engineers running
#             standard incident-response playbooks, and as
#             companion CLI to the Atuin Desktop application.
#
# Author:  Atuin Inc. (atuinsh organization on GitHub) —
#          startup founded by Ellie Huxtable (creator of the
#          original atuin shell-history sync tool).  atuin/
#          desktop released 2024; atuin-run binary continues
#          development through 2026 with regular releases.
# Source:  https://github.com/atuinsh/desktop
#          https://github.com/atuinsh/desktop/blob/main/crates/atuin-run/src/main.rs
#          https://github.com/atuinsh/desktop/blob/main/crates/atuin-run/src/app.rs
#          https://github.com/atuinsh/desktop/blob/main/crates/atuin-run/Cargo.toml
# CLI:     crates/atuin-run/src/app.rs — uses clap 4.x derive
#          (`#[derive(Parser)]`) with positional runbook +
#          --non-interactive flag.  Headline library: **textwrap**
#          (clap is well-documented across many Rust completions;
#          textwrap is the new variant being documented here,
#          opening Axis 12).
# Library: textwrap (https://github.com/mgeisler/textwrap)
#          ("textwrap" — Martin Geisler (mgeisler on GitHub) —
#           released 2017 as "An efficient and powerful Rust
#           library for word wrapping text".  Distinct from
#           every previously-documented Rust library by being
#           narrowly-focused on TERMINAL TEXT WRAPPING +
#           INDENTATION + FORMATTING for the visible-width-aware
#           output that CLI help text + man pages + terminal
#           UI labels need:
#             1. WORD-WRAPPING with multiple algorithms:
#                  - First-fit (default, fast)
#                  - Optimal-fit (Knuth-Plass dynamic programming,
#                    minimizes "raggedness" via squared-distance
#                    cost function)
#             2. WIDTH-AWARE for terminal width — handles ANSI
#                escape sequences (strips them via strip-ansi),
#                wide CJK characters (uses unicode-width crate),
#                emoji (correctly computes width-2)
#             3. INDENTATION CONTROL — initial_indent + subsequent_
#                indent options for hanging-indent paragraphs:
#                  textwrap::wrap("Long text...", textwrap::
#                      Options::new(40).initial_indent("* ").
#                      subsequent_indent("  "))
#                  → "* First line of long text..."
#                    "  continuation indented..."
#             4. FILL VS WRAP — fill() joins wrapped lines into
#                single \n-separated string; wrap() returns
#                Vec<String> of individual lines
#             5. TERMINAL_SIZE INTEGRATION — `termwidth()` returns
#                current terminal width via the terminal_size
#                crate
#             6. HYPHENATION via optional `hyphenation` feature —
#                Knuth-Liang hyphenation patterns for proper
#                soft-hyphen insertion in many languages
#             7. CLAP INTEGRATION — clap 4.x uses textwrap
#                internally for wrapping --help output to
#                terminal width)
# License: MIT (atuin-run); MIT (textwrap)
# Status:  atuin-run — part of atuinsh/desktop (2,418 stars
#          combined repo); textwrap — 520+ stars on mgeisler/
#          textwrap, ~80M crates.io downloads, foundational
#          dependency of clap (the dominant Rust CLI parser
#          uses textwrap for --help formatting), FuelLabs/sway
#          (Fuel smart contract language, 61k stars), PyO3/
#          maturin (Python-Rust bridge), arxanas/git-branchless,
#          gitbutlerapp/gitbutler (20k stars), VladimirMarkelov/
#          ttdl, rust-av/Av1an, atuinsh/desktop (THIS), and 800+
#          Rust CLIs needing terminal text wrapping.
