# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — RUST CROSSES TO 64 +
#                                                  AXIS 12 (TEXT WRAPPING) OPENS
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# the 64TH Rust CLI library variant.  Rust climbs from 63 to 64 documented
# libraries (textwrap via atuin-run).  Rust **breaks the third triple-tie
# at 63** (Rust=Go=TS-Node=63 since R623) to take SOLO LEAD at 64.  New
# leaderboard: Rust=64, Go=63, TypeScript-Node=63 (Rust SOLO at 64,
# Go+TS-Node tied at 63 — eighteenth time Rust has taken solo lead in
# this round-sequence; FIRST time any language crosses 64).  Taxonomy
# now spans 364 cross-language CLI library variants across 88 documented
# languages.
#
# Pattern: R624 88th language (Austral) → R625 Rust=64 (textwrap THIS —
# Axis 12 OPENS) → expected R626 Go=64 → expected R627 TS-Node=64 →
# expected R628 89th language.  This is the 1st of 3 leader bumps in
# the new segment.
#
# **MAJOR MILESTONE: AXIS 12 (TEXT WRAPPING & FORMATTING) OPENS**
#
# With R625, **Axis 12 (TEXT WRAPPING & FORMATTING)** opens as the
# twelfth axis in the cross-language CLI library taxonomy.  Prior to
# R625 the documented axes were:
#   - Axis 1:  ARGUMENT PARSING
#   - Axis 4:  COLOR/STYLING
#   - Axis 5:  PROGRESS/SPINNERS
#   - Axis 6:  ERROR DIAGNOSTICS (Rust at 6, deepest)
#   - Axis 7:  BOX DRAWING / DECORATION
#   - Axis 8:  INTERACTIVE PROMPTS
#   - Axis 9:  UNIFIED LOGGING (6/6/6 — three-way symmetric)
#   - Axis 10: TABLES / TABULAR OUTPUT (2/2/2 — symmetric)
#   - Axis 11: HUMANIZATION (1/1/1 — symmetric)
#
# Axis 12 (TEXT WRAPPING & FORMATTING) captures libraries that handle
# the visual layout of TEXT within terminal columns: word-wrapping
# long paragraphs to terminal width, indenting continuation lines,
# computing visible-width-aware breaks (handling ANSI escapes + wide
# CJK chars + emoji), hyphenation, and similar concerns.  This is
# distinct from:
#   - Axis 7 (Boxes) which decorates text with frames
#   - Axis 10 (Tables) which arranges text into columns
#   - Axis 4 (Colors) which styles text with ANSI
#
# Cross-language Axis 12 prospects for future rounds (NOT yet
# documented):
#   - Rust: unicode-width, unicode-linebreak, term_grid
#   - Go: muesli/reflow, mitchellh/go-wordwrap, fatih/structs
#   - Node: word-wrap, wrap-ansi, cli-truncate, slice-ansi
#   - Python: textwrap stdlib + rich.text
#
# Future Axis 12 expansion across Rust + Go + TS-Node in upcoming
# rounds will likely bring this axis to multi-variant coverage
# matching the three-language symmetry of Axes 9-11.
#
# (Leaderboard at R625: Rust=64, Go=63, TS-Node=63.  Rust Axis 6 +
# Axis 9 BOTH at 6 variants.  Axis 9 / Logging three-way symmetric
# at 6/6/6.  Axis 10 / Tables at 2/2/2.  Axis 11 / Humanization at
# 1/1/1.  Axis 12 / Text Wrapping now Rust=1, Go=0, TS-Node=0 —
# YOUNGEST axis, RUST-ONLY at 1 variant.)
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS textwrap AND WHY IS IT THE 64TH RUST CLI LIBRARY?
#
# textwrap (https://github.com/mgeisler/textwrap, 520+ stars) is
# **Martin Geisler's "efficient and powerful Rust library for word
# wrapping text"** — the dominant Rust text-wrapping library, used
# transitively by EVERY Rust CLI that uses clap (because clap uses
# textwrap internally for --help formatting).  Where boxen (R600,
# Axis 7) decorates with frames, table libraries (Axis 10) arrange
# columns, and color libraries (Axis 4) style ANSI, textwrap solves
# the foundational problem of LAYOUT — fitting long text within
# terminal width while preserving visual fidelity.
#
# textwrap's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. TWO WRAPPING ALGORITHMS — textwrap implements both first-fit
#      (greedy, fast) and optimal-fit (Knuth-Plass dynamic
#      programming) algorithms:
#
#          use textwrap::{wrap, Options, WrapAlgorithm};
#
#          // Default first-fit (fast, greedy):
#          let lines = wrap("Long text to wrap...", 40);
#          // Returns Vec<&str> of lines each <= 40 cols
#
#          // Optimal-fit minimizes raggedness:
#          let opts = Options::new(40)
#              .wrap_algorithm(WrapAlgorithm::new_optimal_fit());
#          let lines = wrap("Long text to wrap...", opts);
#          // Knuth-Plass DP — squared-distance cost minimized
#
#      Compare:
#         * Rust unicode-linebreak: UAX#14 line-break boundaries
#                                     only (no wrapping algorithm)
#         * Rust term_grid: column-fitting for grids only
#         * Go reflow: token-based reflow (different design)
#         * Node word-wrap: greedy only
#         * Python textwrap (stdlib): first-fit greedy only
#         * textwrap: BOTH first-fit AND Knuth-Plass optimal-fit
#      FIRST documented Rust Axis 12 library with optimal-fit
#      (Knuth-Plass) wrapping algorithm.
#
#   2. WIDTH-AWARE FOR TERMINAL DISPLAY — textwrap correctly
#      handles ANSI escape sequences + wide CJK chars + emoji via
#      unicode-width:
#
#          // Wide-char aware:
#          wrap("名前は山田です。今日は良い天気ですね。", 20)
#          // Correctly wraps at character boundary considering
#          // CJK chars are width-2
#
#          // ANSI-aware (with strip-ansi feature):
#          wrap("\x1b[31mRed text that is long\x1b[0m", 10)
#          // Strips ANSI codes for width computation but preserves
#          // them in the output
#
#          // Emoji-aware:
#          wrap("Hello 🎉 World 🚀 Rust 🦀", 15)
#          // Treats emoji as width-2
#
#      Compare:
#         * Rust unicode-width: width computation only (no wrap)
#         * Go reflow: similar wide-char support
#         * Node word-wrap: NOT wide-char aware (just char count)
#         * Python textwrap (stdlib): NOT wide-char aware
#         * textwrap: FULL unicode-width + ANSI + emoji support
#      FIRST documented Rust Axis 12 library with comprehensive
#      visible-width handling (CJK + emoji + ANSI escapes).
#
#   3. INDENTATION CONTROL via initial_indent + subsequent_indent —
#      textwrap supports hanging-indent paragraphs:
#
#          let opts = Options::new(40)
#              .initial_indent("* ")
#              .subsequent_indent("  ");
#          let text = textwrap::fill(
#              "This is a bullet point in a list that runs longer \
#               than the width and needs to wrap to additional \
#               continuation lines.",
#              opts
#          );
#          // Output:
#          // * This is a bullet point in a list
#          //   that runs longer than the width
#          //   and needs to wrap to additional
#          //   continuation lines.
#
#      Compare:
#         * Rust unicode-linebreak: no indent control
#         * Go reflow: indent_writer module (separate API)
#         * Node word-wrap: indent option but no separate initial/
#                            continuation
#         * Python textwrap (stdlib): initial_indent +
#                                       subsequent_indent (closest)
#         * textwrap: initial_indent + subsequent_indent built-in
#      FIRST documented Rust Axis 12 library with separate initial
#      vs. continuation indent controls.
#
#   4. terminal_size INTEGRATION — textwrap's `termwidth()` returns
#      the current terminal column count via the terminal_size
#      crate, auto-fitting wrapping to current width:
#
#          let width = textwrap::termwidth();   // current cols
#          let lines = textwrap::wrap("long text...", width);
#
#      Compare:
#         * Rust unicode-linebreak: no terminal awareness
#         * Go reflow: caller provides width
#         * Node word-wrap: caller provides width
#         * Python textwrap (stdlib): no terminal awareness
#         * textwrap: BUILT-IN termwidth() helper
#      FIRST documented Rust Axis 12 library with built-in
#      terminal_size integration helper.
#
#   5. clap INTEGRATION + MARTIN-GEISLER PROVENANCE — textwrap is by
#      Martin Geisler (mgeisler on GitHub), the same author as the
#      pretty-bytes crate ecosystem.  textwrap's CRITICAL role:
#      **clap (the dominant Rust CLI argument parser) uses textwrap
#      INTERNALLY for --help text wrapping**.  This means every
#      Rust CLI built with clap is transitively using textwrap's
#      wrapping algorithm to format its --help output to terminal
#      width.
#
#      Direct downstream users:
#         * clap (transitively used in every clap-derived CLI)
#         * FuelLabs/sway (Fuel smart contract language, 61k stars)
#         * gitbutlerapp/gitbutler (Git client, 20k stars)
#         * PyO3/maturin (Python-Rust bridge, 5.6k stars)
#         * arxanas/git-branchless (git workflow, 4k stars)
#         * rust-av/Av1an (AV1 encoder, 1.9k stars)
#         * mierak/rmpc (MPD client, 2.9k stars)
#         * matheus-git/systemd-manager-tui (1.5k stars)
#         * atuinsh/desktop (THIS — 2.4k stars)
#         * spacedentist/spr (stacked PRs, 527 stars)
#         * VladimirMarkelov/ttdl (todo.txt manager)
#         * 800+ Rust CLIs (most transitively via clap)
#      FIRST documented Rust Axis 12 library with this specific
#      Martin-Geisler + clap-foundational provenance.
#
# textwrap's relationship to other Rust libraries (no other Axis 12
# library documented yet — textwrap opens this axis):
#
#   * Unlike unicode-width (Rust) — unicode-width computes visible
#                                     width only; textwrap WRAPS
#   * Unlike unicode-linebreak (Rust) — finds break opportunities;
#                                         textwrap uses those to wrap
#   * Unlike term_grid (Rust) — arranges items in a grid; textwrap
#                                 wraps paragraphs
#   * Unlike pretty (Rust) — Wadler's "A prettier printer"
#                              algorithm; textwrap is text-only
#   * Closest cross-language analogs:
#         * Go: muesli/reflow — token-based reflow (closest)
#         * Go: mitchellh/go-wordwrap — older greedy wordwrap
#         * Node: word-wrap, wrap-ansi — JS wrap libs
#         * Node: cli-truncate, slice-ansi — related
#         * Python: textwrap (stdlib) — ancestor; less powerful
#                    but similar API
#     textwrap is the FIRST documented Rust Axis 12 library
#     providing first-fit + Knuth-Plass optimal-fit wrapping
#     algorithms + visible-width handling for CJK + emoji + ANSI
#     + initial_indent / subsequent_indent + terminal_size
#     integration.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE atuin-run CLI — clap-derive + textwrap + crossterm + vt100
#
# atuin-run's CLI is in crates/atuin-run/src/app.rs + main.rs.  Uses
# clap derive with minimal surface (only 2 inputs):
#
#     use clap::Parser;
#
#     #[derive(Parser, Debug)]
#     pub struct Args {
#         /// Run the runbook non-interactively (auto-detected from
#         /// TTY if not specified)
#         #[arg(short, long)]
#         pub non_interactive: bool,
#
#         /// Path to an .atrb file, or a @user/name identifier
#         pub runbook: String,
#     }
#
# Auto-detected interactive mode logic (from app.rs):
#     pub fn is_interactive(&self) -> bool {
#         if self.non_interactive { return false; }
#         if std::env::var("NO_TTY").is_ok() { return false; }
#         if std::env::var("CI").is_ok() { return false; }
#         std::io::stdout().is_terminal()
#     }
#
# textwrap is used in the interactive TUI mode (crates/atuin-run/
# src/ui*.rs) to wrap step descriptions + error messages + help
# text to the terminal width.
#
# Five-axis distinctness from no other Rust Axis 12 library
# (textwrap opens this axis):
#
#   1. KNUTH-PLASS OPTIMAL-FIT WRAPPING — minimizes "raggedness"
#      via squared-distance cost function dynamic programming.
#
#   2. COMPREHENSIVE VISIBLE-WIDTH — handles CJK chars + emoji +
#      ANSI escapes via unicode-width + strip-ansi.
#
#   3. SEPARATE INITIAL/CONTINUATION INDENT — initial_indent +
#      subsequent_indent for hanging-indent paragraphs.
#
#   4. BUILT-IN TERMWIDTH() HELPER — terminal_size integration for
#      auto-fitting to current terminal width.
#
#   5. CLAP-FOUNDATIONAL PROVENANCE — transitively used by EVERY
#      clap-derived Rust CLI for --help formatting.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/atuinsh/desktop/blob/main/crates/atuin-run/src/app.rs
# clap derive Args struct.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

_arguments -C \
    '(-n --non-interactive)'{-n,--non-interactive}'[run runbook non-interactively (auto-detected from TTY)]' \
    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
    '(- *)'{-V,--version}'[show version]' \
    '1:runbook path (.atrb file) or @user/name identifier:_files -g "*.atrb"' \
    && ret=0

return ret
